## Hallucination Report

### CRITICAL: `message` vs `msg` — All Three Plans Are Wrong

**Every single `SoulLoadError` construction in ALL THREE plans uses `message:` as the field name.**

| Plan | Example                                           | Should be                           |
| ---- | ------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| v1   | `new SoulLoadError({ message: "..." })`           | `new SoulLoadError({ msg: "..." })` |
| v2   | `new SoulLoadError({ message, soulName: ... })`   | `{ msg: message, soulName: ... }`   |
| v3   | `new SoulLoadError({ message: "...", soulName })` | `{ msg: "...", soulName }`          |

This affects every error-remapping code block, cache-miss error messages, and validation checklists across all three plans. The same applies to `SoulNotFoundError`, `ManifestParseError`, and `FileSystemError` — ALL of them use `msg` not `message` in the actual source.

**Severity: HIGH** — Using `message` will cause runtime errors. The `Data.TaggedError` constructor expects the exact field name matching the type definition. `new SoulLoadError({ message: "x" })` creates an object where `e.msg` is `undefined` because `message` is not a known property of the type. `Data.TaggedError` extends `Error` which has its own `.message` property, but the plans construct with `message` as a _data field_, not `Error.message`.

