# TP-007: Replace `catchAll(() => succeed(null))` Anti-Pattern in Tests

## Status: Approved for Implementation

| Scope                           | Status                       |
| ------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| `tests/services/loader.test.ts` | ✅ **Changes planned below** |
| `src/loader.ts`                 | ❌ Out of scope (see §6)     |
| `src/persistence.ts`            | ❌ Out of scope (see §6)     |
| `src/commands.ts`               | ❌ Out of scope (see §6)     |

## 1. Summary

Remove the `Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed(null))` anti-pattern from all success-path tests in `tests/services/loader.test.ts`. The `catchAll(null)` pattern silently converts typed Effect failures into opaque `null` values, losing error diagnostics, type information, and interrupt detection.

`it.effect` already has built-in error handling — it captures the `Exit` via `Effect.exit`, calls `Cause.prettyErrors()`, and throws the first error as a plain JS Error that Vitest formats with full stack traces ([source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/blob/82996bce/packages/vitest/src/internal/internal.ts#L17-L37)). Removing `catchAll` is a pure diagnostic improvement: tests that failed before (via `expect(null).not.toBeNull()`) will now fail with the actual `SoulLoadError` message.

**Total change:** ~8 lines removed (the `.pipe(Effect.catchAll(...))` wrappers), ~4 redundant `expect(...).not.toBeNull()` assertions removed, non-null assertions (`!`) dropped from type-narrowed expressions. **No lines added.**

## 2. Codebase Scope

