# Research: Effect-TS Error Handling Best Practices for SoulSpecLoader

## Summary

Effect-TS provides three distinct catch combinators — `catchAll` (typed failures only), `catchAllDefect` (unexpected defects only), and `catchAllCause` (everything including interrupts). The authoritative guidance is: **in interior code** (per-item iteration, middleware), use `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` to preserve fiber interrupt propagation; reserve `catchAllCause` for **system boundaries** only (HTTP mappers, top-level handlers). For iteration patterns that skip failed items, use `Effect.forEach` with `{ mode: "either" }`, `Effect.partition`, or `Effect.allSuccesses` rather than manual catch-and-null patterns. Logging severity should follow the Cause variant: `WARN` for `Fail`, `ERROR` for `Die`, and interrupts should propagate uncaught (or be `DEBUG`-logged at boundaries).

## Findings

### 1. `catchAll` catches only typed failures — NOT defects or interrupts

`Effect.catchAll` only operates on the typed error channel `E`. It does **not** catch `Die` (defects from `Effect.die` or thrown exceptions) or `Interrupt` (fiber cancellation). This is the #1 mistake in Effect-TS codebases.

```typescript
// This catches SoulLoadError (typed E) but NOT defects or interrupts
Effect.catchAll((error: SoulLoadError) => Effect.succeed(null));
```

The effect-advanced/SKILL.md says: _"`catchAll` does NOT catch defects — this is the #1 error handling mistake."_ [Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/SKILL.md)

The Effect official docs confirm: "`catchAll` receives only the typed error value `E`" while "`catchAllCause` receives the full `Cause<E>`." [Source](https://deepwiki.com/Effect-TS/effect/2.4-cause-and-error-handling)

### 2. `catchAllCause` catches everything — appropriate ONLY at system boundaries

`Effect.catchAllCause` catches the full `Cause<E>` tree including `Fail`, `Die`, and `Interrupt`. The Effect docs explicitly state: _"There is no sensible way to recover from defects. The functions we're about to discuss should be used only at the boundary between Effect and an external system, to transmit information on a defect for diagnostic or explanatory purposes."_ [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/)

The agentskills reference reinforces: _"Only use `catchAllCause` / `catchAllDefect` at system boundaries (top-level error handlers, HTTP response mappers)."_ [Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/SKILL.md)

When `catchAllCause` absorbs an `Interrupt` (fiber cancellation), it silently swallows the termination signal — the fiber won't know it should shut down.

### 3. `catchAllDefect` catches only `Die` causes

`Effect.catchAllDefect` catches only unexpected defects (`Die`). It does **not** catch typed failures (`Fail`) or fiber interruptions (`Interrupt`). This makes it safe to use in interior code alongside `catchAll` — interrupts propagate through naturally. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/#catchalldefect)

### 4. Proper replacement for `catchAllCause(() => Effect.succeed(null))` patterns

In **interior code** (e.g., per-soul iteration in `loadAllSouls`), replace:

```typescript
// BAD: swallows interrupts and defects silently
Effect.catchAllCause(() => Effect.succeed(null));
```

With:

```typescript
// GOOD: typed failures logged, defects logged and re-thrown, interrupts propagate
Effect.catchAll((e) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    yield* Effect.logWarning(`[loader] Failed to load soul "${entry}": ${e.message}`);
    return null as SoulManifest | null;
  }),
).pipe(
  Effect.catchAllDefect((defect) =>
    Effect.gen(function* () {
      yield* Effect.logError(`[loader] Defect loading soul "${entry}"`, defect);
      return yield* Effect.die(defect); // re-throw — defects should not be swallowed
    }),
  ),
);
```

The key insight: **interrupts (fiber cancellation) are never matched by `catchAll` or `catchAllDefect`**, so they propagate automatically to the parent fiber. `catchAllCause` would catch and silently swallow them. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/) and [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/blob/7b8165f4/packages/effect/src/Cause.ts)

### 5. Interrupt (fiber cancellation) — must propagate in interior code; use `Cause.isInterruptType` at boundaries

**Interior code rule:** Never catch interrupts. `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` naturally leave interrupts unhandled. Any handler attached via `ensuring` or `onInterrupt` runs regardless when interruption occurs.

**Boundary rule:** At system boundaries (e.g., top-level run loop, CLI entry point), use `Effect.catchAllCause` with explicit discrimination:

```typescript
Effect.catchAllCause((cause) => {
  if (Cause.isInterruptType(cause)) {
    // Log briefly and re-interrupt
    yield * Effect.logDebug("[loader] Interrupted during soul loading");
    return yield * Effect.interruptAs(Cause.fiberId(cause));
  }
  if (Cause.isDieType(cause)) {
    yield * Effect.logError("[loader] Defect at boundary", Cause.pretty(cause));
    return yield * Effect.fail(new SoulLoadError({ message: "...", cause }));
  }
  // Fail-type — map to SoulLoadError
  return yield * Effect.fail(new SoulLoadError({ message: "...", cause }));
});
```

The Effect official docs confirm: "Interruptions occur when a fiber is interrupted... Each interruption records which fiber initiated it via a `FiberId`." [Source](https://deepwiki.com/Effect-TS/effect/2.4-cause-and-error-handling)

### 6. Logging severity for Fail vs Die vs Interrupt

| Cause variant                    | Log level                   | Rationale                                              |
| -------------------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| `Fail` (expected/typed error)    | `Effect.logWarning`         | Anticipated business condition — not a system bug      |
| `Die` (unexpected defect)        | `Effect.logError`           | Programming bug, invariant violation, impossible state |
| `Interrupt` (fiber cancellation) | Not caught in interior code | At boundaries: `Effect.logDebug` then re-interrupt     |

The Effect documentation states: "Use `Effect.die` when encountering unexpected conditions in your code that should not be handled as regular errors but instead represent unrecoverable defects." [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/)

The agentskills reference table confirms: | Failures (expected) — "You intend to handle it at call site" | Defects (unexpected) — "Bug or impossible state" | Recovery: "Only at system boundaries." [Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/SKILL.md)

### 7. Per-item failure handling in iteration — Effect's own patterns

Effect provides several built-in patterns for collecting successes while handling per-item errors:

- **`Effect.partition`** — Runs all effects, returns `[failures[], successes[]]`, error channel is `never`. Ideal for batch-loading where you want to separate successes and failures. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/error-accumulation/#partition)

- **`Effect.forEach` with `{ mode: "either" }`** — Runs all effects, returns `Either<E, A>[]`. Each result is either a `Left(error)` or `Right(value)`. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/parallel-and-sequential-errors/)

- **`Effect.allSuccesses`** — Collects only successful values, completely ignores failures. Returns `never` in error channel. [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/commit/7ddd65415b65ccb654ad04f4dbefe39402f15117)

- **`Effect.validateAll`** — Like `Effect.forEach` but collects all failures in the error channel (as an array). [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/error-accumulation/#validateall)

For the `loadAllSouls` pattern, `Effect.partition` or a manual loop with `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` (preserving interrupts) is appropriate since the process is sequential over directory entries with filesystem interaction.

### 8. `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` as replacement for `catchAllCause` — authoritative guidance

The pattern is:

```typescript
// In non-boundary/interior code:
yourEffect.pipe(
  Effect.catchAll((typedError) => {
    yield * Effect.logWarning(`Handling expected error: ${typedError.message}`);
    return fallbackValue;
  }),
  Effect.catchAllDefect((defect) => {
    yield * Effect.logError(`Defect encountered`, defect);
    return yield * Effect.die(defect); // must re-throw
  }),
);
```

This is the authoritative replacement because:

- `catchAll` handles expected typed errors (`Fail`) — logs at `WARN`
- `catchAllDefect` handles unexpected defects (`Die`) — logs at `ERROR` and re-throws
- Interrupts (`Interrupt`) propagate through untouched
- No `catchAllCause` needed unless at a system boundary

The Effect docs confirm: "catchAllDefect does not handle expected errors (like those from Effect.fail) or execution interruptions (like those from Effect.interrupt)." [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/#catchalldefect)

The agentskills reference explicitly states: _"Only use `catchAllCause` / `catchAllDefect` at system boundaries. `catchAll` does NOT catch defects."_ [Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/references/error-handling.md)

### 9. Application to SoulSpecLoader's `loadAllSouls`

The current `loadAllSouls` uses sequential iteration with `Effect.catchAll` + `Effect.catchAllCause` both returning `null`. This can be improved to:

**Per-item skip pattern (interior):**

```typescript
for (const entry of entries) {
  if (seen.has(entry)) continue;
  seen.add(entry);

  const result =
    yield *
    loadSoul(entry, level).pipe(
      Effect.catchTags({
        SoulNotFoundError: (e) => {
          yield * Effect.logWarning(`[loader] Soul "${entry}" not found`);
          return null as SoulManifest | null;
        },
        ManifestParseError: (e) => {
          yield * Effect.logWarning(`[loader] Invalid manifest for "${entry}": ${e.message}`);
          return null as SoulManifest | null;
        },
        FileSystemError: (e) => {
          yield * Effect.logWarning(`[loader] FS error for "${entry}": ${e.message}`);
          return null as SoulManifest | null;
        },
        // SoulLoadError from loadSoul's own boundary handling
        SoulLoadError: (e) => {
          yield * Effect.logWarning(`[loader] Failed to load "${entry}": ${e.message}`);
          return null as SoulManifest | null;
        },
      }),
      Effect.catchAllDefect((defect) =>
        Effect.gen(function* () {
          yield* Effect.logError(`[loader] Unexpected defect loading soul "${entry}"`, defect);
          return yield* Effect.die(defect); // re-throw
        }),
      ),
    );

  if (result) {
    results.push(result);
  }
}
```

**Outer boundary protection (system boundary):**
The existing `Effect.catchAllCause` on the outer `loadSoul` and `loadAllSouls` methods is appropriate as a system boundary — it maps all remaining causes (including unexpected defects after logging) to a `SoulLoadError`. However, the interrupt handling should be explicit:

```typescript
Effect.catchAllCause((cause) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    if (Cause.isInterruptType(cause)) {
      // Don't log; just propagate interrupt
      return yield* Effect.interruptAs(Cause.fiberId(cause));
    }
    if (Cause.isDieType(cause)) {
      yield* Effect.logError("[loader] Defect", Cause.pretty(cause));
    } else {
      yield* Effect.logWarning("[loader] Unexpected error", Cause.pretty(cause));
    }
    return yield* Effect.fail(
      new SoulLoadError({ message: "Error loading soul: Unexpected error", cause }),
    );
  }),
);
```

Or even better: use `Effect.exit` at the boundary for explicit pattern matching on `Exit`, which gives access to the full `Cause` structure. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/#exit)

### 10. `Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed(null))` for fs.exists guard

The `Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed(false))` pattern in `getAllSoulsInternal` for `fs.exists` is a **pragmatic exception** — it's guarding against an `fs.exists` filesystem error (a brittle dependency), not swallowing domain errors. The Effect docs note that `catchAll` does NOT catch defects or interrupts, so this pattern is safe here: filesystem defects still propagate, interrupts still propagate, only the expected `FileSystemError` (if any) is caught. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/expected-errors/#catchall)

Similarly, the `Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed(null as string | null))` in `getSoul` for `resolveSoulPath` is a practical convenience that allows the cache to work even if path resolution partially fails, and is safe because `catchAll` leaves defects and interrupts intact.

