# Research: Effect-TS Error Handling Best Practices for SoulSpecLoader

## Summary

Effect-TS provides three distinct catch combinators — `catchAll` (typed failures only), `catchAllDefect` (unexpected defects only), and `catchAllCause` (everything including interrupts). The authoritative guidance is: **in interior code** (per-item iteration, middleware), use `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` to preserve fiber interrupt propagation; reserve `catchAllCause` for **system boundaries** only (HTTP mappers, top-level handlers). For iteration patterns that skip failed items, use `Effect.forEach` with `{ mode: "either" }`, `Effect.partition`, or `Effect.allSuccesses` rather than manual catch-and-null patterns. Logging severity should follow the Cause variant: `WARN` for `Fail`, `ERROR` for `Die`, and interrupts should propagate uncaught (or be `DEBUG`-logged at boundaries).

## Findings

### 1. `catchAll` catches only typed failures — NOT defects or interrupts

`Effect.catchAll` only operates on the typed error channel `E`. It does **not** catch `Die` (defects from `Effect.die` or thrown exceptions) or `Interrupt` (fiber cancellation). This is the #1 mistake in Effect-TS codebases.

```typescript
// This catches SoulLoadError (typed E) but NOT defects or interrupts
Effect.catchAll((error: SoulLoadError) => Effect.succeed(null));
```

The effect-advanced/SKILL.md says: _"`catchAll` does NOT catch defects — this is the #1 error handling mistake."_ [Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/SKILL.md)

### 2. `catchAllCause` catches everything — appropriate ONLY at system boundaries

`Effect.catchAllCause` catches the full `Cause<E>` tree including `Fail`, `Die`, and `Interrupt`. The Effect docs explicitly state: _"There is no sensible way to recover from defects. The functions we're about to discuss should be used only at the boundary between Effect and an external system, to transmit information on a defect for diagnostic or explanatory purposes."_ [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/)

When `catchAllCause` absorbs an `Interrupt` (fiber cancellation), it silently swallows the termination signal — the fiber won't know it should shut down.

### 3. `catchAllDefect` catches only `Die` causes

`Effect.catchAllDefect` catches only unexpected defects (`Die`). It does **not** catch typed failures (`Fail`) or fiber interruptions (`Interrupt`). This makes it safe to use in interior code alongside `catchAll` — interrupts propagate through naturally. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/unexpected-errors/#catchalldefect)

### 4. Proper replacement for `catchAllCause(() => Effect.succeed(null))` patterns

In **interior code** (e.g., per-soul iteration in `loadAllSouls`), replace:

```typescript
// BAD: swallows interrupts and defects silently
Effect.catchAllCause(() => Effect.succeed(null));
```

With:

```typescript
// GOOD: typed failures logged, defects logged and re-thrown, interrupts propagate
Effect.catchAll((e) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    yield* Effect.logWarning(`[loader] Failed to load soul "${entry}": ${e.message}`);
    return null as SoulManifest | null;
  }),
).pipe(
  Effect.catchAllDefect((defect) =>
    Effect.gen(function* () {
      yield* Effect.logError(`[loader] Defect loading soul "${entry}"`, defect);
      return yield* Effect.die(defect); // re-throw — defects should not be swallowed
    }),
  ),
);
```

The key insight: **interrupts (fiber cancellation) are never matched by `catchAll` or `catchAllDefect`**, so they propagate automatically to the parent fiber.

### 5. Interrupt (fiber cancellation) — must propagate in interior code; use `Cause.isInterruptType` at boundaries

**Interior code rule:** Never catch interrupts. `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` naturally leave interrupts unhandled.

**Boundary rule:** At system boundaries, use `Effect.catchAllCause` with explicit discrimination:

```typescript
Effect.catchAllCause((cause) => {
  if (Cause.isInterruptType(cause)) {
    yield * Effect.logDebug("[loader] Interrupted during soul loading");
    return yield * Effect.interruptAs(Cause.fiberId(cause));
  }
  if (Cause.isDieType(cause)) {
    yield * Effect.logError("[loader] Defect at boundary", Cause.pretty(cause));
    return yield * Effect.fail(new SoulLoadError({ message: "...", cause }));
  }
  return yield * Effect.fail(new SoulLoadError({ message: "...", cause }));
});
```

[Source](https://deepwiki.com/Effect-TS/effect/2.4-cause-and-error-handling)

### 6. Logging severity for Fail vs Die vs Interrupt

| Cause variant                    | Log level                   | Rationale                                              |
| -------------------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| `Fail` (expected/typed error)    | `Effect.logWarning`         | Anticipated business condition — not a system bug      |
| `Die` (unexpected defect)        | `Effect.logError`           | Programming bug, invariant violation, impossible state |
| `Interrupt` (fiber cancellation) | Not caught in interior code | At boundaries: `Effect.logDebug` then re-interrupt     |

[Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/SKILL.md)

### 7. Per-item failure handling in iteration — Effect's built-in patterns

- **`Effect.partition`** — Runs all effects, returns `[failures[], successes[]]`, error channel is `never`. Ideal for batch-loading. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/error-accumulation/#partition)
- **`Effect.forEach` with `{ mode: "either" }`** — Runs all effects, returns `Either<E, A>[]`. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/parallel-and-sequential-errors/)
- **`Effect.allSuccesses`** — Collects only successful values, ignores failures. Returns `never` in error channel. [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/commit/7ddd65415b65ccb654ad04f4dbefe39402f15117)
- **`Effect.validateAll`** — Like `forEach` but collects all failures in error channel. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/error-accumulation/#validateall)

### 8. `catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` as replacement for `catchAllCause` — authoritative pattern

```typescript
// In non-boundary/interior code:
yourEffect.pipe(
  Effect.catchAll((typedError) => {
    yield * Effect.logWarning(`Expected error: ${typedError.message}`);
    return fallbackValue;
  }),
  Effect.catchAllDefect((defect) => {
    yield * Effect.logError(`Defect encountered`, defect);
    return yield * Effect.die(defect); // must re-throw — never swallow defects
  }),
);
```

This is the authoritative replacement because:

- `catchAll` handles expected typed errors (`Fail`) — logs at `WARN`
- `catchAllDefect` handles unexpected defects (`Die`) — logs at `ERROR` and re-throws
- Interrupts (`Interrupt`) propagate through untouched

The agentskills reference explicitly states: _"Only use `catchAllCause` / `catchAllDefect` at system boundaries. `catchAll` does NOT catch defects."_ [Source](https://github.com/trancong12102/agentskills/blob/main/effect-advanced/references/error-handling.md)

### 9. Application to `getSoul`'s `Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed(null))` for path resolution

The `Effect.catchAll(() => Effect.succeed(null as string | null))` in `getSoul` for `resolveSoulPath` is a **pragmatic exception** — it guards against path resolution failure so the cache key can fall back to the soul name directly. Because `catchAll` does **not** catch defects or interrupts, filesystem defects still propagate and fibers can still be cancelled. This pattern is safe for this narrow utility purpose. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/error-management/expected-errors/#catchall)

### 10. `Effect.catchAllCause` on `loadSoul` and `loadAllSouls` outer boundary

The existing `catchAllCause` on the outer boundary is architecturally correct (system boundary), but should explicitly handle `Interrupt`:

```typescript
Effect.catchAllCause((cause) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    if (Cause.isInterruptType(cause)) {
      return yield* Effect.interruptAs(Cause.fiberId(cause));
    }
    if (Cause.isDieType(cause)) {
      yield* Effect.logError("[loader] Defect", Cause.pretty(cause));
    }
    return yield* Effect.fail(
      new SoulLoadError({ message: "Error loading soul: Unexpected error", cause }),
    );
  }),
);
```

