# Research: Effect-TS DRY/Redundancy Elimination for Error Handling Pipelines

## Summary

Effect-TS provides powerful compile-time error tracking via discriminated tagged errors, but there is **no built-in exhaustive `catchTags`** (Issue #6023 is open, requesting one). The idiomatic pattern is a **two-tier architecture**: internal fine-grained errors mapped to a unified consumer error type at the public boundary. Platform errors (`SystemError`, `BadArgument` from `@effect/platform`) have `_tag` fields that are catchable with `catchTag`/`catchTags`. Removing `catchAll` entirely is not recommended — `catchAll` (called `Effect.catch` in v4) is the only mechanism that guarantees the error channel resolves to `never`, and it acts as a valuable safety net against unanticipated error shapes. The `Data.TaggedError.fromCause()` factory (PR #3935, merged) is the most direct DRY helper for eliminating `new SoulLoadError({message:..., cause:...})` repetition.

## Findings

### 1. Exhaustive catchTags coverage is possible but has no compiler guarantee

`Effect.catchTag("SomeTag", handler)` type-narrows the error union by removing the matched tag. Chaining multiple `catchTag` calls — or using `Effect.catchTags({Tag1: ..., Tag2: ...})` — progressively reduces the union. If every `_tag` in the union is handled, the error channel becomes `never`. **However, Effect has no built-in exhaustive variant of `catchTags`** — the library intentionally allows partial handling (remaining errors just propagate). An open feature request (Issue #6023) asks for an exhaustive helper, and PR #4783 added a "remain/fallback" callback parameter to `catchTags` for unlisted tags. In the current stable API, there is **no compiler error** if you miss a tag — unhandled tags simply remain in the error channel. [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/issues/6023) [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/pull/4783)

### 2. Platform errors are fully catchable by tag at the top level, but not at the reason level

`@effect/platform` defines `PlatformError = BadArgument | SystemError`, both as `Schema.TaggedError` classes with `_tag` fields `"BadArgument"` and `"SystemError"` respectively. `SystemError` also has a `reason` field typed as a `Schema.Literal` union of 11 strings (`NotFound`, `PermissionDenied`, `TimedOut`, etc.).

- ✅ You CAN catch all platform errors exhaustively: `Effect.catchTags({BadArgument: ..., SystemError: ...})` leaves `never`.
- ❌ You CANNOT use `catchTag("NotFound", ...)` to catch only NotFound SystemErrors — `catchTag` dispatches on `_tag`, not `reason`. To discriminate by reason, you need `catchIf` with a predicate or `catchAll` + manual discrimination.
- The `BadArgument` and `SystemError` tags are stable and unlikely to gain new variants in minor releases, but the `SystemErrorReason` literal union could theoretically grow. [Source](https://deepwiki.com/Effect-TS/effect/5.4-file-system-and-path-operations) [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/blob/main/packages/platform/src/Error.ts)

### 3. There is no built-in check for "already wrapped" — the architecture is the answer

Effect-TS provides **no runtime function** to check whether an error has already been wrapped by Effect error handling. `Cause.contains` exists but checks Cause structure, not error-wrapping status. The idiomatic avoidance of double-wrapping is **architectural**:

- **Two-tier error design**: Internal methods expose domain-specific tagged errors (`SoulNotFoundError`, `ManifestParseError`, `FileSystemError`). Public methods map ALL of these into a single consumer-facing type (`SoulLoadError`) via `catchTags` at the boundary.
- **`mapError` at integration points**: Transform external/platform errors into domain errors at the single point where they enter the system, not in each consumer.
- **No recursive wrapping**: If the public API always catches+remaps at the boundary and consumers only interact with `SoulLoadError`, double-wrapping cannot occur by design.
- **Limitation**: There is no assertion or guard that prevents someone from calling `Effect.mapError(SoulLoadError.fromCause())` on an effect that already fails with `SoulLoadError`. This is a discipline/convention enforcement gap. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/guides/error-management/expected-errors) [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/blob/7b8165f4/packages/effect/src/Cause.ts)

### 4. Removing catchAll entirely: correctness vs future-proofing tradeoffs

| Approach                            | Correctness                                                                                         | Future-Proofing                                                                                             | Compile-time Safety                                                              |
| ----------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Exhaustive catchTags only**       | Error channel = `never` when all tags handled.                                                      | If a new error variant appears (e.g., new platform error type), it silently propagates — no compiler error. | Partial — unhandled tags just remain in error channel (no exhaustiveness check). |
| **catchTags + catchAll safety net** | Error channel = `never` at the cost of a catch-all at runtime.                                      | A new error type is caught and remapped rather than propagating. Non-breaking for consumers.                | Full — but the catchAll hides unexpectedly added error types.                    |
| **catchTags + catchAllDefect**      | Typed errors must be fully handled or they propagate; defects/ interrupts are logged but re-thrown. | More disciplined: unexpected typed errors propagate to caller instead of being swallowed.                   | Better separation of concerns.                                                   |

**Key insight from the Effect team's own patterns**: The official docs consistently show `Effect.catchTag(...)` + `Effect.catch(...)` (formerly `catchAll`) as a deliberate chain — `catch` is not an anti-pattern but a safety net. In v4 (current docs), `Effect.catch` is the recommended final handler after specific tag catches. The "all must be typed" ideal is aspirational; real codebases have dynamic error shapes at integration boundaries.

**The `Effect.catchAll` vs `Effect.catchAllDefect` vs `Effect.catchAllCause` distinction** matters: `catchAll` (typed errors only) + `catchAllDefect` (defects, re-thrown) + leaving `Interrupt` unhandled is the most principled pattern, preserving the distinction between expected errors, programming bugs, and fiber cancellation. `catchAllCause` should only be at system boundaries. [Source](https://mintlify.com/Effect-TS/effect-smol/migration/error-handling) [Source](https://effect.website/docs/guides/error-management/expected-errors)

### 5. `Data.TaggedError.fromCause()` — the direct DRY helper for error wrapping

PR #3935 (merged) added `Data.Error.fromCause()` and `Data.TaggedError.fromCause()` — factory constructors that produce a function wrapping errors into the tagged error type.

```typescript
class SoulLoadError extends Data.TaggedError("SoulLoadError")<{
  readonly message: string;
  readonly soulName?: string;
  readonly cause?: unknown;
}> {}

// Factory: pre-binds all non-cause fields
const wrapError = SoulLoadError.fromCause({ message: "Failed to load soul" })

  // Usage with mapError — eliminates new SoulLoadError({...}) repetition
  .pipe(Effect.mapError(wrapError));
// This is a (cause: unknown) => SoulLoadError function

// With Effect.try for external code:
Effect.try({
  try: () => riskyOperation(),
  catch: wrapError,
});
```

**Before (current SoulSpecLoader pattern)** — repeated boilerplate:

```typescript
Effect.catchTag("FileSystemError", (e) =>
  Effect.fail(
    new SoulLoadError({
      message: `File system error: ${getErrorMessage(e.cause)}`,
      cause: e.cause,
    }),
  ),
);
```

**After (with `fromCause`)** — zero repetition:

```typescript
const wrapFsError = SoulLoadError.fromCause({
  message: "File system error", // static message prefix
});

Effect.catchTag("FileSystemError", (e) => Effect.fail(wrapFsError(e.cause)))
  // Or even simpler with Effect.mapError:
  .pipe(Effect.mapError((e) => wrapFsError(e.cause)));
```

**Additional patterns for reducing boilerplate**:

- **Custom `.message` getter on `SoulLoadError`**: Compute the message string dynamically instead of pre-formatting at every call site, similar to the `SystemError.message` pattern in @effect/platform source.
- **`Schema.Defect` for the `cause` field**: Using `Schema.Defect` (instead of `unknown`) makes error serializable and self-documenting; the schema handles `Error` name+message extraction automatically.
- **`Effect.fn` for auto-tracing**: Wrapping the public loader methods with `Effect.fn` gives free stack traces with definition/call-site locations. [Source](https://github.com/Effect-TS/effect/pull/3935) [Source](https://www.effect.solutions/error-handling)

### 6. Current SoulSpecLoader architectural assessment

The current SoulSpecLoader already follows the recommended two-tier pattern: internal errors (`SoulNotFoundError`, `ManifestParseError`, `FileSystemError`, `NoSoulsFoundError`) caught by `catchTags` and remapped to `SoulLoadError`. However, there are DRY opportunities:

- **`catchAll` + `catchAllDefect` duplication**: Both blocks manually construct `new SoulLoadError({...})` with near-identical logic, only the log level and message prefix differ.
- **`getErrorMessage` helper**: This is a `(unknown) => string` function that exists because `unknown` error types don't have `.message`. Moving to `fromCause()` factories would make this unnecessary at wrapping sites.
- **Missing `catchAllCause` at the outermost boundary**: The current `catchAll` only handles typed errors; `catchAllDefect` handles defects. But if a platform error like `BadArgument` gets through (not caught by `catchTags`), it would hit `catchAll` and be wrapped. This **works correctly** but the outer `catchAll` acts as the implicit exhaustiveness handler — the issue is that if `catchTags` misses a tag, you won't know at compile time.
- **No `fromCause` usage yet**: The `fromCause` factory (available in recent Effect versions) would directly eliminate the `new SoulLoadError({...})` repetition across all catch blocks. [Source](https://effect.website/docs/guides/error-management/expected-errors)

